{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1346].
  {panel}

HTML emails received contain three graphic images which load from the JIRA instance.  However, if you don't have a live connection, the email appears to be blank for a few seconds until the email browser times out attempting to load the images.

To improve performance, suggest removing the graphics or embedding them into the message so they can be viewed even if not connected.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1340].
  {panel}

It would be nice to be able to define filters specific for a certain project. Filters often have a meaning within the context of a project. Therefore it would be nice to see them on the project's dashboard/homepage. 

Same idea could be applied for assigned issues within the context of this project.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1335].
  {panel}

a) Make logging easier to configure from within application.  I should be able to change logging levels at runtime.

b) Be able to view logs from within JIRA.  Perhaps use a file viewer, or a 'memory appender' to achieve this.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1321].
  {panel}

Filter subscription is a very very interesting feature. Now we can only specify interval based recurrence.

It could be enhanced to be able to specify the recurrence the same way Outlook allows to specify event recurrence (attached image).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1320].
  {panel}

I use a mutli-tab browser. Thus I tend to start different "find/filters" in different views. But it seems that jira is storing the current filter in the session context. So, if I'm in the middle of scanning issues from a filter and then swap to another tab to check something out--eg, see issues for a component--when I go back to the tab with the original list, the previous/next buttons don't continue where I left them, but rather are not bound to the component issues context.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1263].
  {panel}

When you release a version, have an option to send an email to everyone watching any issue that is fixed in that version.

This allows you to notify the people waiting on issues to be fixed, that there is a new version which fixes their problem.

This idea was prompted by Jason Pell, who took the time to notify me that a new version of the pell multipart parser was available.

I noticed the new 'Configure Dashboard' page doesn't render the arrow buttons (>, <, ^, etc) correctly. Suggested fix: give the widget a class name like:

<input type="submit" value="&gt;" class="foo">

Then a little CSS:

.foo {
  padding-left : 2px;
  padding-right : 2px;
}

That should improve it.
